==English==

===Etymology===
{{wikipedia}}
Middle English ''armonye'' < Old French ''armonie'' < Latin ''[[harmonia|harmŏnĭa]]'' < Greek [[ἁρμονία]] (joint, union, agreement, concord of sounds), related to [[ἁρμός]] (joint, groove, slit), < Proto-Indo-European '''*ar-ti-''' < '''*ar-''' (to fit together).

===Pronunciation===
*(US)
**{{IPA|/ˈhɑrməni/}}
**{{SAMPA|/"hArm@ni/}}
*{{audio|en-us-harmony.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun-reg-y|harmon|y}}

# [[agreement]] or [[accord]]
# a pleasing [[combination]] of [[element]]s, or [[arrangement]] of [[sound]]s
# {{music}} the [[academic]] [[study]] of [[chord]]s
# {{music}} two or more [[note]]s played [[simultaneously]] to produce a chord

